item.text: There is a distinction between decentralised and distributed structure. Centralised, Decentralised, Distributed, Federated - are all ways to describe different network architectures. Read more on [http://networkcultures.org/unlikeus/resources/articles/what-is-a-federated-network/ Network Cultures]
It is important to keep in mind that these terms can be confusing - system can be decentralised to certain extent, or some processes can be decentralised while other are not.
In IT decentralised and distributed infrastructures can involve servers or be serverless.
Most structures of legal entities are designed in a centralized way. To prototype distributed organisation

Most structures of legal entities are designed in a centralized way. The idea of flat or non hierarchical organizations is popular, yet in practice as soon as a relatively decentralized structure incorporates a legal entity, while enjoying some privileges of legal personhood it looses resilience and ability to scale or be as inclusive as a decentralized multi community like structure would be.
New forms of legal entities can be created though the same principles of decentralised consensus described on this wiki.
There also ways of "paper prototyping" the structure of distributed organization.
